{
  "skillId": "distribute-negative-multiplier",
  "atomType": "R",
  "theory": {
    "intro": "When the term in front of a bracket is negative, you still multiply it by every term inside — but the negative multiplier changes the sign of each product. Getting the sign of each term right is the whole skill.",
    "facts": [
      "The distributive law still applies: $-a(b+c) = -ab - ac$ — the negative outside multiplies **every** term inside.",
      "Use the sign rule on each product: a negative times a **positive** is **negative**, a negative times a **negative** is **positive**.",
      "A subtraction inside is a negative term: $-3(2x-5)$ means $-3 \\times 2x$ and $-3 \\times (-5) = +15$, so the sign **flips**.",
      "A bare minus in front, like $-(x-3)$, means multiply by $-1$: every sign inside flips."
    ],
    "steps": [
      "Multiply each inside term by the outside term.",
      "Apply the sign rule to each product.",
      "Write the expanded expression."
    ]
  },
  "practice": {
    "foundation": [
      {
        "q": "Expand $-2(x+4)$.",
        "a": "$-2x-8$",
        "solution": [
          { "math": "$-2(x+4)$" },
          { "math": "$= -2(x) - 2(4)$", "note": "Multiply each" },
          { "math": "$= -2x-8$", "note": "Apply signs" }
        ]
      },
      {
        "q": "Expand $-4(3b+2)$.",
        "a": "$-12b-8$",
        "solution": [
          { "math": "$-4(3b+2)$" },
          { "math": "$= -4(3b) - 4(2)$", "note": "Multiply each" },
          { "math": "$= -12b-8$", "note": "Apply signs" }
        ]
      },
      {
        "q": "Expand $-3(x-2)$.",
        "a": "$-3x+6$",
        "solution": [
          { "math": "$-3(x-2)$" },
          { "math": "$= -3(x) - 3(-2)$", "note": "Multiply each" },
          { "math": "$= -3x+6$", "note": "Apply signs" }
        ]
      },
